I went here with my girlfriend around 9:15 pm to grab a couple dessert crepes after dinner. We ordered as soon as we were seated because we didn’t want to take up space very long just to have dessert. We received our food (which was pretty good) promptly and ate quickly. I immediately asked for the check. We were in the restaurant for no more than 20 minutes at this point. Upon receiving our check we were quite rudely told “In the future, know we don’t allow people to come in just for dessert.” My date and I were over the top kind and conscious of the fact that we didn’t want to hold a table long but we still received this response. So even though our bill was over $20 before tip, we were only there for less than 20 minutes, and it was so late no one else was trying to come into the restaurant, we were still treated as though we were a nuisance. I rarely rarely review restaurants but I wanted to make sure I expressed how negative my experience was. You don’t ever have to worry about me coming back just for dessert.

Pates & Traditions is a quaint, charming corner cafe that looks like a slice of the French countryside. It looks like it was decorated by a French grandma with lots of kitchy French items covering almost every inch of wall space. The decor works well mostly because matches the theme and style of the menu perfectly.  The service here is warm and accommodating. We went for brunch — around 12pm on a Sunday and there was no wait to be seated; unlike many other places in this neighborhood where the brunch waits can be 1 hour plus. The menu features about a dozen themed crepes, and a handful of omelettes, french toast, and a couple traditional French dishes. I had the “oeufs Perigord” ($16) and my mouth was in heaven. Eggs are baked in a crock with mushrooms and cream, then topped with chunks of foie gras. 🙀 The foie melts into everything and you have a yolky, creamy, foie mix which is perfect spooned onto toast. The flavors and textures were amazing to me — i was so happy to discover this dish. My boyfriend’s crepe came filled with potatoes and was topped with generous chunks of Camembert ($12). We shared the French toast ($9) and it was some of the nest we’ve ever had. Custardy, crispy, a bit sweet, it was the perfect share item. The portions are modest and the prices are very reasonable for what you get which is nice.  We cant wait to come back for more — especially in summer, when they have outdoor seating on this still quiet corner of Williamsburg.

So I'm French living in the U.S. I went to this restaurant with my American girlfriend who's very enthusiast about France. We ordered the foie gras, a crepe and pasta with Roquefort sauce. The foie gras was very expensive for the quantity, pasta and crepe were ok/pretty good. But the main issue was the service, pushing to add expensive ingredient and making excuses to only serve the most expensive wine. At the end they told us that it's cash only. Weird for a restaurant in NY making me wonder about the reasons behind (IRS?). Bottom line, as a French expatriate, I think that opening a restaurant in the U.S. is a great idea but if you are smart about it you should mix what you find great about France (food) with the American quality of service (that I really appreciate) And unfortunately it was not the case... This restaurant reminded me of the tourist restaurants close to Notre Dame in Paris, not interested about their reputation because they have new tourists coming everyday.

My favorite was the La normande which had chicken, mushrooms, and swiss cheese. So decadent and delicious. I also made fun of my other friend for ordering the Thai curry crepe at a French restaurant but it was actually really good. The goat cheese and fig one was delicious as well. Basically order anything except for the shrimp one :(

This place is amazing! It's cute and casual; nice for a meal with friends and suitable for a date.
